{
  "text": "In a previous study, GFAP-Cre-driven, shRNAmediated partial loss of BCCIP in brain tissue was sufficient to cause neurodegeneration and microcephaly accompanied by p53 activation [CITATION_1] . However, microcephaly and neurodegeneration were rescued by Trp53 deletion and this led to tumor development [CITATION_2] , suggesting synergy between BCCIP loss and p53 loss in the development of medulloblastoma. In this study, when the K14-Cre-driven Bccip-CKD mice were crossed with the same conditional Trp53 mice as used previously [CITATION_3] , we did not observe any synergy in tumor formation or overall survival. The lack of synergies between p53 loss and BCCIP loss in this mouse model is in agreement with the observation of human breast cancer (Table 1) . We also speculate that since p53 deficiency alone caused tumor development with a relatively short latency (when compared to BCCIP deficiency) it may have masked the opportunity for cells with concurrent p53 and BCCIP loss to develop breast cancer.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "18167443",
